{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01YSQBRRsdt45r9f3juxhbnk","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Also I noticed that the previous successful run used a different WAR name in the server.xml. The server.xml references `order-jakarta.war` but Open Liberty might be using `order-app`. Let me check - in the last successful run it said `Starting application order-app`. The issue is I need to make sure the names are consistent. Let me also check: the `persistence-unit` name in `persistence.xml` is `orderPU` but repositories reference it as `@PersistenceContext(unitName = \"orderPU\")`. Let me verify this is correct and the server.xml application name matches the WAR file.\n\nActually wait, the previous successful run worked fine with the `order-jakarta.war` name. The only issue now is the timing of the startup initializer. Let me also check the persistence configuration - the `@PersistenceContext(unitName = \"orderPU\")` in the repository needs to match the persistence.xml. But the previous successful run worked fine for data initialization so the PU name was correct.\n\nThe real issue was just that `@Initialized(ApplicationScoped.class)` fires before JPA is ready. The `@Startup` EJB singleton approach should fix it.\n\nLet me rebuild:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":985,"cache_read_input_tokens":140212,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":985,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":405},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e80e1467-8d50-4d14-a21d-b94c86ec6299","uuid":"a77163b5-9c53-45b2-adc0-12b4c8941abb"}
