{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01RLJFHXZB6UmXKiinRd7AQB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Wait, `setEnableSpringELCompiler` is Spring-specific and won't help here. The actual issue is OGNL expression restrictions in Thymeleaf 3.1. The fix for non-Spring Thymeleaf is to configure the OGNL expression evaluator's restricted classes. Let me look at how to properly allow access.\n\nIn Thymeleaf 3.1, the restriction is controlled by the `ognl.TypeConverter` and security configuration. The proper fix for standalone Thymeleaf (without Spring) is to set the `org.thymeleaf.standard.expression.StandardExpressionObjectFactory` to be unrestricted, or to use the Thymeleaf configuration property.\n\nActually, the simplest approach is to convert our entity data to simple Maps before passing to Thymeleaf, or to use a `WebContext`. Let me try the most robust approach - convert entities to Maps in the controller:\n\nActually, looking at this more carefully, in Thymeleaf 3.1, the OGNL access restriction is for types that are not explicitly whitelisted. The solution is to configure the `StandardDialect` to allow access to our package. Let me check the Thymeleaf 3.1 API:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1841,"cache_read_input_tokens":57258,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1841,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":367},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e80e1467-8d50-4d14-a21d-b94c86ec6299","uuid":"fdf2cc58-da69-42e2-82f3-8ec21ee5cafe"}
