{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01SdVh2jQvxPSgsXwA8aVnAH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Also, I need to check the repositories - they use `@PersistenceContext` which gives them a JTA EntityManager. Within the BMT transaction from StartupInitializer, the EntityManager should properly participate. Let me check one repo to confirm:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":660,"cache_read_input_tokens":81441,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":660,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":171},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e80e1467-8d50-4d14-a21d-b94c86ec6299","uuid":"20bd1aa4-72d0-46ec-881e-7a595b57f41a"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01SdVh2jQvxPSgsXwA8aVnAH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_bdrk_01Mp73fPd6Xx4GamM3Hb9uc6","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__persistence__order__quarkus__jakarta/run_1/output/src/main/java/jakarta/tutorial/order/repository/CustomerOrderRepository.java"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":660,"cache_read_input_tokens":81441,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":660,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":171},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e80e1467-8d50-4d14-a21d-b94c86ec6299","uuid":"98523f92-fa0a-4ad1-94c6-e5e90237ca89"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Mp73fPd6Xx4GamM3Hb9uc6","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package jakarta.tutorial.order.repository;\n     2→\n     3→import jakarta.tutorial.order.entity.CustomerOrder;\n     4→import jakarta.enterprise.context.ApplicationScoped;\n     5→import jakarta.persistence.EntityManager;\n     6→import jakarta.persistence.PersistenceContext;\n     7→import java.util.List;\n     8→import java.util.logging.Logger;\n     9→import jakarta.transaction.Transactional;\n    10→\n    11→@ApplicationScoped\n    12→public class CustomerOrderRepository {\n    13→    private static final Logger logger = Logger.getLogger(CustomerOrderRepository.class.getName());\n    14→\n    15→    @PersistenceContext(unitName = \"orderPU\")\n    16→    private EntityManager em;\n    17→\n    18→    @Transactional\n    19→    public void createOrder(Integer orderId, char status, int discount, String shipmentInfo) {\n    20→        try {\n    21→            CustomerOrder order = new CustomerOrder(orderId, status, discount, shipmentInfo);\n    22→            em.persist(order);\n    23→            logger.info(\"Created order ID \" + orderId);\n    24→        } catch (Exception e) {\n    25→            logger.severe(\"Failed to create order ID \" + orderId + \": \" + e.getMessage());\n    26→            throw new RuntimeException(e.getMessage(), e);\n    27→        }\n    28→    }\n    29→\n    30→    public List<CustomerOrder> getOrders() {\n    31→        try {\n    32→            return em.createNamedQuery(\"findAllOrders\", CustomerOrder.class).getResultList();\n    33→        } catch (Exception e) {\n    34→            logger.severe(\"Failed to get orders: \" + e.getMessage());\n    35→            throw new RuntimeException(e.getMessage(), e);\n    36→        }\n    37→    }\n    38→\n    39→    @Transactional\n    40→    public void removeOrder(Integer orderId) {\n    41→        try {\n    42→            CustomerOrder order = em.find(CustomerOrder.class, orderId);\n    43→            if (order != null) {\n    44→                em.remove(order);\n    45→                logger.info(\"Removed order ID \" + orderId);\n    46→            }\n    47→        } catch (Exception e) {\n    48→            logger.severe(\"Failed to remove order ID \" + orderId + \": \" + e.getMessage());\n    49→            throw new RuntimeException(e.getMessage(), e);\n    50→        }\n    51→    }\n    52→\n    53→    public double getOrderPrice(Integer orderId) {\n    54→        try {\n    55→            CustomerOrder order = em.find(CustomerOrder.class, orderId);\n    56→            if (order == null) {\n    57→                throw new RuntimeException(\"Order ID \" + orderId + \" not found\");\n    58→            }\n    59→            return order.calculateAmmount();\n    60→        } catch (Exception e) {\n    61→            logger.severe(\"Failed to get price for order ID \" + orderId + \": \" + e.getMessage());\n    62→            throw new RuntimeException(e.getMessage(), e);\n    63→        }\n    64→    }\n    65→\n    66→    @Transactional\n    67→    public void adjustOrderDiscount(int adjustment) {\n    68→        try {\n    69→            List<CustomerOrder> orders = em.createNamedQuery(\"findAllOrders\", CustomerOrder.class).getResultList();\n    70→            for (CustomerOrder order : orders) {\n    71→                int newDiscount = order.getDiscount() + adjustment;\n    72→                order.setDiscount(Math.max(newDiscount, 0));\n    73→                em.merge(order);\n    74→            }\n    75→            logger.info(\"Adjusted discount by \" + adjustment);\n    76→        } catch (Exception e) {\n    77→            logger.severe(\"Failed to adjust discounts: \" + e.getMessage());\n    78→            throw new RuntimeException(e.getMessage(), e);\n    79→        }\n    80→    }\n    81→}\n    82→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e80e1467-8d50-4d14-a21d-b94c86ec6299","uuid":"6e61ef5a-902c-4416-b752-e8a583fad422"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01RGubg1epe2MhFrmTqybNej","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The repositories have `@Transactional` on their mutating methods. Since the `StartupInitializer` using BMT already has a `utx.begin()`, the `@Transactional(REQUIRED)` annotation on repository methods will try to use the existing transaction. However, the issue is that `@Transactional` is a CDI interceptor which doesn't see the BMT transaction context.\n\nActually, thinking about this more carefully - when the `StartupInitializer` (BMT EJB) calls `orderConfigService.createData()` which is a CDI bean, and `createData()` calls repository methods with `@Transactional`, there's a potential nested transaction issue. The BMT's `UserTransaction` should propagate, and the `@Transactional(REQUIRED)` should join it.\n\nBut to avoid any complications, let me keep it simpler. Let me remove `@Transactional` from the repo methods during startup and instead have them all share one transaction:\n\nActually, the cleanest approach: keep the `@Transactional` annotations on the repos (they work fine for web requests), and for the startup, just use BMT in the singleton. The repos' `@Transactional` should be `REQUIRED` by default, which means \"join existing or create new.\" Since the BMT has already started one, they should join.\n\nLet me rebuild and test:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1304,"cache_read_input_tokens":82101,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1304,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":449},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e80e1467-8d50-4d14-a21d-b94c86ec6299","uuid":"14dfc294-4a71-44fc-abcb-59618dad222f"}
